===Etymology===
Middle English ''broun'' (the color brown from 13th century) < Old English ''[[brun|brūn]]'' (dark, shining) < Proto-Germanic ''*brunaz'' < Proto-Indo-European ''*bher-'' (shining, brown). Cognates include Danish ''[[bruin]]'', Icelandic ''[[brnn]]'', Swedish ''[[brun]]'', German ''[[braun]]'', Lithuanian ''[[brunas]]'', ''[[beras]]'', Sanskrit ''[[babhru]]'', and Medieval Latin ''brunus'', Spanish ''[[bruno]]'', French ''[[brun]]''. Confer [[bruin]], [[beaver]], [[burnish]], [[brunette]].

